                                                                                                               SPORT BRIEFS
                                                      Mahela, Kumar dropped  Colombo: Skipper Mahela Jayawardene and vice-captain Kumar Sangakkara were left out of Sri Lanka rsquo;s 15-man squad for the Twenty20 match against India next week.
  Tillekeratne Dilshan will lead the side.  Meanwhile, Sri Lanka named two uncapped players in their squad for the two-Test tour of Pakistan starting this month.  The squads  Twenty20: Tillekeratne Dilshan (Capt.), Sanath Jayasuriya, Jehan Mubarak, Chamara Kapugedera, Chamara Silva, Indika de Saram, Lasith Malinga, Dilhara Fernando, Fervez Mahroof, Kaushal Weeraratne, Malinga Bandara, Jeevantha Kulatunga, Dilhara Lokuhettige, Mahela Udawatte, Thilan Thushara.  Tests vs Pakistan: Mahela Jayawardene (Capt.), Malinda Warnapura, Tharanga Paranavitana, Kumar Sangakkara, Thilan Samaraweera, Tillekeratne Dilshan, Prasanna Jayawardene, Chaminda Vaas, Muttiah Muralidharan, Ajantha Mendis, Chamara Kapugedera, Fervez Mahroof, Dilhara Fernando, Thilan Thushara, Suranga Lakmal.  Race for No.1  Calcutta: The International Cricket Council (ICC) president David Morgan and chief executive Haroon Lorgat Wednesday opened the countdown to the top-table clash between South Africa and Australia that begins later this month by taking possession of the ICC Test championship mace. The top prize in the game rsquo;s ultimate format is up for grabs in the three-match series with the winners taking first place on the ladder, securing $175,000 in prize money and giving themselves the right to be called the best side in the world.  Border awards  Melbourne: Under-fire Australian captain Rick Ponting shared the Allan Border Medal with his deputy Michael Clarke. This is the first time in the 10-year history of the award that two people have jointly awarded the top honour. Ponting and Clarke collected 41 votes apiece.   Sunny honour  Mumbai: Sunil Gavaskar was Wednesday conferred with an honorary doctorate by the Dr DY Patil University in Navi Mumbai.  Football meet   Mumbai: Aspiring footballers in the country have another chance to fulfil their dream of playing at the lsquo;Theatre of Dreams rsquo; with the return of the Budweiser 6v6 Cup for its second edition.  India draw 2-2   Chandigarh: India held European champions Holland 2-2 in the first match of the second leg of the four-nation Punjab Gold Cup hockey tournament here Wednesday.   Prakash up   New Delhi: Prakash Amritraj advanced to the second round of the $ 50,000 ATP Challenger event in Dallas after defeating Michael Yani of the host nation 6-3, 6-2 in the opening round. He will next face sixth seed Brazilian Ricardo Mello.   
